q17b: This is an interesting issue. Statistically, it seems (at least at first glance) that the outcomes are equivalent. With either program, any individual in the group of 600 people appears to have a 2/3 chance of dying. The difference, of course, is that with Plan A, if one individual lives (or dies), then all do, whereas with Plan B, at least some individuals (1/3 of the entire group) are guaranteed to live (although, of course, 2/3 are guaranteed to die). It seems that purely mathematical reasoning is of little use, although by discarding that approach quickly, it is possible that I overlooked a subtle detail that might have made a mathematically-based decision more clear. So I tried to come up with an analogy that didn't involve disease. I supposed that a journey had to be made, but with a choice of conveyances: either (A) a creaky old airplane big enough to hold 600 people (but which had a 2/3 chance of crashing en-route and killing everyone aboard), or (B) 600 drivers in individual automobiles on a dangerous winding road on which 400 drivers would die in accidents, but 200 would certainly reach their destinations. Although the analogy isn't perfect (drivers can choose to be careful, whereas airline passengers have little to say about how their aircraft is maintained or operated), I saw two advantages to (B): first, that there was some sense of control (albeit illusory) over one's destiny, and second, that there was a guarantee of at least some survivors. A third advantage to choice (B) (considered independently of its possible effects on the individual victims of the illness) was its comparatively salutary effect on the overall quality of the human gene pool: it seems clear that the results of choice (A) depended heavily on the efficacy of the treatment plan; regardless of whether everyone survived or perished, the gene pool would become neither better nor worse than it was previously, since there was no favorable selection for those individuals better adapted to fighting off the illness. The results of plan (B) would appear to depend more heavily on each individual's natural resistance to the illness; the survivors would presumably have demonstrated an increased resistance that was likely at least partially inherited. After the pandemic ended and the victims were reunited with the remainder of the human race, a larger fraction of the remaining members of the species would be resistant to the disease, thus improving the overall gene pool (albeit at the expense of the some of the individual members of the species).    Finally, one can take a contrarian point of view, and ask which choice a devil's advocate would prefer. Although there is a broadly accepted moral imperative to save as many lives as possible (all conventional analyses of the situation will implicitly assume that saving human lives is a good thing), one can imagine that certain extreme environmentalists, ZPG members, and adherents of Malthus might prefer a choice that is most likely to reduce the excess human population by as many individuals as possible, and to prevent any improvement in the gene pool. Choice (A) has a very good chance of reducing the human population by 600 individuals, and even if the 600 were to get lucky and survive, their survival would have no effect to improve the gene pool. So the devil wins at least something either way with this choice.

If Program B doesn't work & the outbreak occured again, then we limit the loss of life to 400 by adopting Program A until we can come up with a better solution.  I strongly believe that we should at least try to save everyone as opposed to letting 400 people die each and every outbreak occurrence.
